The Hanover WWTP=s accidental release prevention program is based upon the following elements:

1.    High level of training for the operators;

2.    Preventative maintenance program for equipment;

3.    Use of state of the art process and safety equipment;

4.    Use of accurate and effective standard operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;

5.    Performance of a Hazard Review of the equipment and procedures; and

6.    Implementation of an auditing and inspection program.

Chemical specific prevention steps include availability of self contained breathing apparatus (SCBA,) awareness of the hazards and toxic properties of chlorine, and the presence of a chlorine gas detector.

No accidental releases of chlorine have occurred at this facility in the past five (5) years.

    The facility has an emergency response program which has been reviewed and coordinated by the Adams County Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) in Gettysburg.  The operation and response procedures are reviewed and updated on an annual basis by the Adams County LEPC.  The Adams County Defensive Hazardous Materials (HAZMAT) Response Team is the designated first-responder in the event of a chlorine or sulfur dioxide leak incident.  This HAZMAT team, however, is trained only at the Technician Level but is not State Certified; they can provide limited support for leak containment.  Under a mutual aid agreement between Adams County and Cumberland County, the Cumberland County Hazardous Materials (HAZMAT) Response Team will provide additional support for chlorine or sulfur dioxide leak repair.  This HAZMAT team is state certified and undergoes extensive training in dealing with a variety of hazardous material incidents, including chlorine and sulfur dioxide gas leaks.  

